                    <span class="result-level">Glucose</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Normal: 70-99 mg/dL (fasting) | High may indicate diabetes; Low may suggest hypoglycemia</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">Calcium</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Normal: 8.5-10.5 mg/dL | Essential for bone health, muscle and nerve function</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">Total Protein</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Normal: 6.0-8.3 g/dL | Low or high levels may indicate various conditions</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">Albumin</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Normal: 3.4-5.4 g/dL | Low levels may suggest liver disease, kidney disease, or malnutrition</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">Globulin</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Normal: 2.3-3.5 g/dL | Elevated levels may indicate infection or chronic inflammation</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">A/G Ratio</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Normal: 1.0-2.5 | Helps evaluate protein balance and liver/kidney function</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">ALT</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Normal: 7-56 U/L | Elevated levels may suggest liver damage</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">AST</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Normal: 10-40 U/L | Elevated levels may indicate liver or heart damage</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">ALP</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Normal: 44-147 U/L | Elevated levels may indicate liver or bone disease</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">Bilirubin</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Total: 0.1-1.2 mg/dL | Elevated levels may indicate liver problems or hemolysis</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">BUN</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Normal: 7-20 mg/dL | Elevated levels may indicate kidney dysfunction or dehydration</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">Creatinine</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Normal: 0.6-1.2 mg/dL | Primary indicator of kidney function</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">BUN/Creatinine Ratio</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Normal: 10-20:1 | Helps determine cause of kidney problems</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">eGFR</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">&gt;60 mL/min/1.73 m² is normal | Lower values indicate reduced kidney function</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">Sodium</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Normal: 136-145 mEq/L | Critical for fluid balance and nerve function</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">Potassium</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Normal: 3.5-5.0 mEq/L | Essential for heart rhythm and muscle function</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">Chloride</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Normal: 98-107 mEq/L | Helps maintain proper pH balance</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="result-row">
                    <span class="result-level">Carbon Dioxide</span>
                    <span class="result-meaning">Normal: 22-29 mEq/L | Indicates acid-base balance</span>
                  </div>
                </div>
                <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 italic mt-4">
                  Note: Reference ranges vary; results should be interpreted by a healthcare provider in context of overall health.
                </p>
              </div>

              <!-- FAQ -->
              <div class="content-section">
                <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
                <div class="faq-container">
                  <details class="faq-item">
                    <summary class="faq-question">Do I need to fast for a CMP?</summary>
                    <p class="faq-answer">Fasting for 8-12 hours is recommended for the most accurate glucose measurement, though other values may still be useful without fasting.</p>
                  </details>
                  
                  <details class="faq-item">
                    <summary class="faq-question">What does the CMP test for?</summary>
                    <p class="faq-answer">The CMP includes 18 tests that evaluate kidney function (BUN, creatinine, eGFR), liver function (ALT, AST, ALP, bilirubin), blood sugar (glucose), electrolyte balance (sodium, potassium, chloride, CO₂), and protein levels (albumin, total protein, globulin) in one comprehensive panel.</p>
                  </details>
                  
                  <details class="faq-item">
                    <summary class="faq-question">How often should I get a CMP?</summary>
                    <p class="faq-answer">For routine health monitoring, annually is typical. Your doctor may recommend more frequent testing if you have chronic conditions.</p>
                  </details>
                  
                  <details class="faq-item">
                    <summary class="faq-question">What can affect my CMP results?</summary>
                    <p class="faq-answer">Dehydration, medications, recent illness, and certain foods can all impact results. Always inform your healthcare provider of these factors.</p>
                  </details>
                </div>
              </div>

